result.execSummary:
The defendant Calvin J Argo-Duffy was found guilty of the following charge(s) in this case.

  • Misdemeanor Battery, a class A misdemeanor, Wisconsin Statutes 940.19(1).
  • Disorderly Conduct, a class B misdemeanor, Wisconsin Statutes 947.01(1).

Charge(s) in this case were read in to this or other case(s). A "read in" charge is a charge that is dismissed as part of a plea agreement, however:

  • The defendant agrees to have the court consider the charge(s) when sentencing for another crime, under Wis. Stats. 973.20(1g)(b); and
  • The defendant cannot be prosecuted for these charge(s) in the future.

Notice to employers: It may be a violation of state law to discriminate against a job applicant because of an arrest or conviction record. Generally speaking, an employer may refuse to hire an applicant on the basis of a conviction only if the circumstances of the conviction substantially relate to the particular job. For more information, see Wisconsin Statute 111.335 and the Department of Workforce Development's publication, Arrest and Conviction Records under the Law.

(Cases 22CF1012, 22CM764 are called at 10:58 AM) Defendant Calvin J Argo-Duffy in court with Attorney Katherine Cook.  Attorney Trenton Piltz in court for State of Wisconsin. 
State in compliance with victim notification requirements. Defense indicates there is an agreement. Defendant does not feel forced in accepting any offers. State recites the joint sentence recommendation. Defendant is advised of charges, maximum penalties, elements of the crime(s) and constitutional rights. Defendant pleads No Contest to amended Count 1- Misdemeanor Battery and Count 2- Disorderly Conduct. Court accepts pleas and finds the Defendant guilty. Remaining charges are dismissed and read in, including all of 22CM764. Defense makes a statement. 
Court orders the Defendant to provide DNA sample, pay the surcharge, Restitution in the amount of $184.92 plus 10% surcharge, Court orders the case is to be expunged once Restitution is paid in full, Court costs. 
Court orders court costs are waived due to Defendant being indigent.
